    "   \"metadata\": {},\n",
    "   \"source\": [\n",
    "    \"# Assignment 1. Exploratory Modeling with JUSTICE\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"**Course:** EPA141A Model Based Decision Making — Delft University of Technology  \\n\",\n",
    "    \"**Model:** JUSTICE\\n\",\n",
    "    \"**Contact:** J.ZatarainSalazar@tudelft.nl  \\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"---\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"## Learning Outcomes\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"After completing this assignment you will be able to:\\n\",\n",
    "    \"1. Verify that the JUSTICE model is installed and runs correctly.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"2. Identify and define **model input uncertainties**.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"3. Use **Latin Hypercube Sampling** to generate a scenario ensemble that spans the uncertainty space.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"4. Run JUSTICE across many scenarios under different policy assumptions and collect the outcomes.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"5. Visualise outcome **distributions**, **pair plots**, and **time series envelopes** to characterise how uncertainty propagates.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"---\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"## Background\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"When building models of complex systems (climate, economy, ecology) we rarely know\\n\",\n",
    "    \"the exact value of every parameter. A damage-function coefficient, a discount rate,\\n\",\n",
    "    \"or a climate sensitivity parameter are all uncertain. **Exploratory modeling** treats\\n\",\n",
    "    \"uncertainty explicitly: we run *many* scenarios, sampling the uncertain parameters\\n\",\n",
    "    \"systematically, and study the resulting spread in model outputs.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"In this assignment we treat four parameters as uncertain:\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"| Symbol | Parameter | Default | Range | Description |\\n\",\n",
    "    \"|--------|-----------|---------|-------|-------------|\\n\",\n",
    "    \"| `ρ` | Pure rate of social time preference | 0.015 | [0.001, 0.030] | Contested in the Stern–Nordhaus debate |\\n\",\n",
    "    \"| `η` | Elasticity of marginal utility | 1.45 | [0.5, 1.5] | Empirical estimates range widely |\\n\",\n",
    "    \"| `δ` | Damage function scale factor | 1.0 | [0.5, 2.0] | Structural uncertainty in damage estimates |\\n\",\n",
    "    \"| `ecs_ensemble` | FaIR ensemble member index | 1 | [1, 1001] | Selects a calibrated ECS parameter set |\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"`ecs_ensemble` is a *physical* uncertainty (how sensitive the climate system is to CO₂),\\n\",\n",
    "    \"while `ρ`, `η`, and `δ` are *normative* uncertainties (contested values in economic ethics).\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"We also compare two **policies** that differ in their emission control rate:\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"| Policy | `ecr_plateau` | Description |\\n\",\n",
    "    \"|--------|--------------|-------------|\\n\",\n",
    "    \"| `no_abatement` | 0.0 | Zero mitigation effort throughout the simulation |\\n\",\n",
    "    \"| `moderate_abatement` | 0.4 | 40 % emission reduction applied from the start |\"\n",
    "   ]\n",
    "  },\n",
    "  {\n",
    "   \"cell_type\": \"markdown\",\n",
    "   \"id\": \"a01-ema-md01\",\n",
    "   \"metadata\": {},\n",
